                        <p> <hi rend="italic">Case at the Hospitals of <name type="place">Alexandria, Va.</name></hi></p><p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 66.&#8212;<name type="person"
                                                key="820">Private William Hitchen</name>, <name
                                                type="organization" key="152">Co. B, 1st N. J.
                                                Cav.</name>; age 25; was admitted <date type="admit"
                                                when="1864-01-26">Jan. 26, 1864</date>, as a case of
                                        quotidian intermittent. The fever was arrested by quinine,
                                        but on <date type="injury" when="1864-01-29">the 29th</date> the patient was seized with pain in the
                                        limbs, headache, some delirium and paralysis of the right
                                        arm and leg, while his tongue became dry and his pulse
                                        frequent. Cups and blisters were applied to the back of the
                                        neck, after which he became quieter and ultimately comatose,
                                        in which condition he remained until death, <date
                                                type="death" when="1864-02-01">February 1</date>.   <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination: The
                                        brain was congested; pus was found on the cerebro-spinal
                                        membranes. The lungs were congested and part of the left
                                        lung hepatized.</p>                        
